                  <handDesc>
                     <!--ACHTUNG! first HandNote comes from writing system in Ethiospare. the others are one for each CHANGE OF HAND-->
                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                        <seg type="script">Mediocre and irregular</seg>
                        <seg type="ink">Black, red (vivid red, vivid vermillion, strong
                           vermillion).</seg>The handwriting is similar, but not identical to that
                        of <ref type="mss" corresp="ESap008">AP-008</ref> and <ref type="mss" corresp="ESap064">AP-064</ref>.
                        <date>Late 17th-18th century</date>
                        <list type="abbreviations">
                           <item>
                              <abbr>ምዕ፡</abbr> for <expan>ምዕራፍ፡ </expan> (e.g., <locus target="#87va">87va</locus>, 88va, 92vb, 83vb)</item>
                           <item>
                              <abbr>ም፡</abbr> for <expan>ምዕራፍ፡ </expan> (e.g., <locus target="#82vb">82vb</locus>)</item>
                        </list>
                        <seg type="rubrication">Rubrication is executed in different tones of red:
                           vivid red (e.g., fols. 3ra-4vb), vivid vermillion (e.g., fol. 15rb),
                           strong vermillion (e.g., fol. 13rb); in some cases it differs even within
                           one fol. (e.g., fols. 7r, 16r, 18r, 31r, 32v). It cannot be excluded that
                           the rubrication was partly executed by a different hand.&#xD; Nomina
                           sacra and the name of the church Ṗarāqliṭos; incipit of Text I-1 (2 red
                           lines alternating with black lines); incipit of Text I-2 (3 red lines
                           above alternating with black lines, 2 red lines below) and its sections;
                           incipit of Text I-3 and its numbers; words ʾǝsaggǝd, "I worship", mǝʿrāf,
                           "chapter" and its abbreviations; elements of the punctuation signs;
                           elements of Ethiopic numerals.&#xD; Lacunae for (rubricated) names
                           occasionally not filled (e.g. fols. 47ra, 98va, 120ra).</seg>
                        
                        <p>It is difficult to determine whether
                           one or more scribes were involved in writing. The handwriting changes from
                           usually mediocre and irregular to careful and neat (e.g., <locus target="#7v">7v</locus>/8r, 63rv, 100v/101r). Irregularities are e.g.,
                           <!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></p>
                        <p> - size of letters significantly
                           differs, also within one column (cp., <locus target="#32va">32va</locus>b,
                           82ra against
                           82vb);<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></p>
                        <p> - space between letters significantly
                           differs (cp., <locus target="#9vb">9vb</locus> against 10ra, 75v against
                           76r,
                           99vb);<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></p>
                        <p> - occasionally the ruling was
                           disregarded: text is written between lines, last ruling line is not used
                           (cp., <locus from="12ra" to="17vb">12ra-17vb</locus>).<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></p>
                        <p> However, a few distinctive features
                           appear, though not quite regularly throughout the entire
                           Ms.:<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></p>
                        <p> - ancient form of 'one' (፩, triangular
                           upwards-oriented)<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></p>
                        <p> - ancient form of 'six' (፮, looking
                           like "compressed" number 'seven')
                           <!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></p>
                        <p> - occasionally short hairlines
                           extending horizontal elements of some letters (e.g. <locus target="#8ra">8ra</locus>: ሔ, ን እ, ይ, ደ,
                           ገ)<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></p>
                        <p> - the right loop of ሠ (in all vowel
                           orders) is of smaller
                           size.<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></p>
                     </handNote>

